			<title>News Mom behind ‘Let’s Go Crazy’ YouTube video wins landmark copyright ruling</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?78274-Mom-behind-‘Let’s-Go-Crazy’-YouTube-video-wins-landmark-copyright-ruling&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Thu, 19 Nov 2015 05:49:03 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Mom behind &#8216;Let&#8217;s Go Crazy&#8217; YouTube video wins landmark copyright ruling (https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/09/15/mom-behind-lets-go-crazy-youtube-video-wins-landmark-copyright-ruling/?tid=article_nextstory) 
 
 
---Quote--- 
In 2007, Stephanie Lenz uploaded to YouTube a...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div><a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/09/15/mom-behind-lets-go-crazy-youtube-video-wins-landmark-copyright-ruling/?tid=article_nextstory" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Mom behind &#8216;Let&#8217;s Go Crazy&#8217; YouTube video wins landmark copyright ruling</a><br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			In 2007, Stephanie Lenz uploaded to YouTube a 29-second video of her two small children parading around her kitchen to Prince&#8217;s song &#8220;Let&#8217;s Go Crazy.&#8221; It was quintessentially cute from the start and got cuter still along the way, especially when the mom asked her 13-month old son &#8220;what do you think of the music?,&#8221; which prompted him to bob up and down with joy on his little push toy. The video was an instant hit and still is, with over 1.3 million views.<br />
<br />
But Universal Studios saw nothing cute about it. <br />
<br />
Responsible for enforcing Prince&#8217;s copyrights, Universal, like other companies, searches YouTube on a regular basis for just such videos. When it came across Lenz&#8217;s &#8220;Let&#8217;s Go Crazy,&#8221; the company&#8217;s lawyer sent a &#8220;takedown notification&#8221; to YouTube. And YouTube did indeed take it down.<br />
<br />
But on Monday, Lenz took down Universal, winning an important ruling from a federal appeals court that has the potential to make companies think twice, or at least think a little harder, before issuing the takedown notifications allowed by a section of the Digital Millennium Copyright Act.<br />
<br />
After the video&#8217;s removal, Lenz sued the company, claiming it had misrepresented its takedown privileges permitted under that law. Specifically, her lawyers said, the company did not stop to consider whether Lenz&#8217;s video amounted to &#8220;fair use&#8221; of Prince&#8217;s song, in which case it would not have been a copyright infringement and not subject to summary takedown.<br />
<br />
The fair use principle is an aspect of copyright law that allows use of a copyrighted work for purposes such as criticism, news reporting, teaching and research. Fair use is what allows a critic, for example, to quote passages from a book or a literary scholar to include parts of a poem in a research paper that happens to be about that poem. It&#8217;s what also permits a newspaper to quote portions of books that make news without getting permission from the publisher.<br />
<br />
The case is an important one for the entertainment and publishing industries, especially with the advent of the Internet and social media, where people routinely appropriate background music for their videos, adding their own little touches along the way.<br />
<br />
Or, as in Lenz&#8217;s case, where they show their children frolicking to some popular song.<br />
<br />
Monday, a panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 9th Circuit held for Lenz, saying that when Universal issued its takedown notice &#8212; asserting with certainty that Lenz was violating Prince&#8217;s copyright &#8212; it did not not consider whether her video was a fair use. If indeed it was a fair use, the company could not have had it removed.<br />
<br />
&#8220;Universal faces liability if it knowingly misrepresented in the takedown notification that it had formed a good faith belief the video was not authorized by the law, i.e., did not constitute fair use,&#8221; wrote Judge Richard C. Tallman for the majority. &#8220;Here, Lenz presented evidence that Universal did not form any subjective belief about the video&#8217;s fair use &#8212; one way or another &#8212; because it failed to consider fair use at all, and knew that it failed to do so.&#8221;<br />
<br />
&#8220;To be clear,&#8221; the panel said, &#8220;if a copyright holder ignores or neglects our unequivocal holding that it must consider fair use before sending a takedown notification, it is liable for damages.&#8221;<br />
<br />
This is not the end of the case, however. To determine whether she&#8217;s entitled to damages, she&#8217;ll have to go back to a trial court and show that Universal knowingly misrepresented its &#8220;good faith&#8221; belief that it had the right under the law to issue the takedown notice.<br />
<br />
Still, the ruling is problematic for the industry for a variety of reasons. As the court pointed out, companies scan thousands, even millions, of Internet postings for copyright infringement using algorithms rather than humans. The more subjective judgment, whether, say, a portion of a movie playing in the background while someone&#8217;s kids are playing in the foreground, may require more human intervention. On the other hand, the court suggested that an algorithm that proved itself capable of making such a determination might be sufficient.<br />
<br />
Ars Technica saw that as an ominous sign. &#8220;The majority&#8217;s near-endorsement of mass takedown routines is telling&#8221; and is &#8220;unlikely to change much about the millions of takedown notices now being sent each year to internet intermediaries.&#8221;<br />
<br />
A spokesman for the Recording Industry Association of America issued a statement on behalf of Universal: &#8220;We respectfully disagree with the court&#8217;s conclusion about the DMCA and the burden the court places upon copyright holders before sending takedown notices. But we are pleased that the Ninth Circuit made it clear that a court may not second guess a copyright owner&#8217;s good faith belief that the fair use does not excuse infringing conduct.&#8221;<br />
<br />
&#8220;I am hopeful we will have fewer improper takedown orders,&#8221; Corynne McSherry, a lawyer with the Electronic Frontier Foundation, which represented Lenz, told the Los Angeles Times. &#8220;Copyright holders now are on notice they have to be more careful.&#8221;<br />
<br />
What does the ruling mean for the average YouTuber? It&#8217;s hard to tell. But reading its definition of &#8220;fair use,&#8221; taken directly from the law and the opinion, could provide some protective tips:<br />
<br />
It may be fair use when &#8220;for purposes such as criticism, comment, news reporting, teaching (including multiple copies for classroom use), scholarship, or research, is not an infringement of copyright. In determining whether the use made of a work in any particular case is a fair use the factors to be considered shall include &#8212;<br />
<br />
<div style="margin-left:40px">(1) the purpose and character of the use, including whether such use is of a commercial nature or is for nonprofit educational purposes;<br />
<br />
(2) the nature of the copyrighted work;<br />
<br />
(3) the amount and substantiality of the portion used in relation to the copyrighted work as a whole; and<br />
<br />
(4) the effect of the use upon the potential market for or value of the copyrighted work.</div><br />
Judge Milan D. Smith, Jr., concurred in part and dissented in part.<br />
<br />
The opinion is <a href="https://consumermediallc.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/lenz-9ca-opinion.pdf" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">here</a>.
			
		<hr />
	</div>
</div></div>

