			<pubDate>Mon, 16 Nov 2015 14:59:15 GMT</pubDate>
			<description>Solesk mentioned in the Fallout 4 thread that he was trying to decide which Xbox One bundle to get. I remember seeing lots of deals for it and thought I would post comparisons, and figured while I was at it I might as well post PS4 and Wii U deals as well. As one preface I want to point out that I...</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Solesk mentioned in the Fallout 4 thread that he was trying to decide which Xbox One bundle to get. I remember seeing lots of deals for it and thought I would post comparisons, and figured while I was at it I might as well post PS4 and Wii U deals as well. As one preface I want to point out that I don't currently know what deals Amazon will be running. They are usually pretty competitive but it's impossible to know if they will be better or the same.<br />
<br />
Most of this will just be a summary of what I found on CAG, but because of the nature of these deals it's still taking more effort than I anticipated. I'm kind of sore with Microsoft for this. Not only do they have an absurd number of different bundles, but they have very short length deals that expire each week, which is why I couldn't find the deals I remembered hearing about. This kind of revolving door bullshit makes it hard to figure out what the best deal is, many of them have already expired, and several others expire just before the Black Friday deals go into effect. It's frustrating and a really bad holiday strategy in my opinion. It's just going to encourage people to keep waiting for the next deal. I'm not sure what the heck they were thinking.<br />
<br />
As a result I'm going to save the Xbox for last, despite it being most relevant to making this thread, simply because of how much shorter the PS4 and Wii U sections will be to read.<br />
<br />
<br />
First, the <b>Wii U</b>. I know a few of you were waiting for deals on this, not sure if you ever got one. I've been tempted myself, largely because of Xenoblade and Mario Maker. I can't decide if I should be annoyed with Nintendo for not having a better deal or not, but their only Holiday deal seems to be to get the system, Splatoon, and Smash Brothers for $250 at Target and Walmart. Bundles with other games are normally $300. So you save $50 and get two popular pack-ins instead of one. <br />
<br />
<br />
The <b>PS4</b> also has one clear bundle deal, netting you the PS4 and the Uncharted Collection (ports of the first three games) for $300. They also have a Battlefront bundle that isn't discounted at $350. So again, you save $50. This deal seems to be available everywhere. The only 1TB option is overly expensive and not getting a discount, unless Amazon or someone does a surprise Cyber Monday deal.<br />
<br />
<br />
Now, the <b>Xbox One</b>, I'm going to start with the Black Friday deals. The best deal seems to be at Target, where you get the 500GB Gears of War bundle with a $60 gift card for $300. This is the only deal after the 21st that provides extra value equal to a free game, as most of the discounts basically amount to, you guessed it, $50 off a normal bundle's price.<br />
<br />
The different Xbox bundles seem to be retailer specific, with Best Buy and Gamespot promising $50 off any bundle. Which means you can get the 1TB Tomb Raider bundle for $350 from Best Buy, or the 1TB Holiday Bundle for $350 from Gamestop. The Holiday Bundle includes Gears of War, Ori and the Blind Forest ($20), and Rare Replay ($30), so it's similar to the cheaper Gears Bundle but with an upgrade to the hard drive as a bonus. Rare Replay is a collection of ports (30 games, maybe 12 worth playing still) and Ori is an excellent 2D platformer (though it's been heavily discounted).<br />
<br />
<br />
Now as far as the current promotions, both Target and Gamestop have a $100 trade in offer for your old system. These both expire the 21st, and while I am not certain, I imagine they require you buy the system immediately. If you are able to let that credit sit an extra week, the Target deal will be much better, though there is also the risk they sell out. Most retailers also have a free game deal that also expires on the 21st.<br />
<br />
So, while the other two platforms have pretty simple options, if you want an Xbox One you have a lot of things to consider.<br />
<br />
<ul><li style="">How important is the 1TB hard drive to you? This is going to be more important to people who plan on buying a lot of games each year and want to have them all available at a moment's notice. I've yet to fill up my 500 gig PS4 yet, though people who don't mix between console and PC will fill theirs up faster. You should be able to fit at least 10 games on there without having to delete stuff.</li><li style="">Do you want to trade in your old console? It nets you an extra $50 off.</li><li style="">Which games you prefer. Do you choose based on retail savings alone, or on what you think you might rather play? This is important in choosing your free game as well. The impetus is on picking something new to get the most value, but if it isn't something you want to play it isn't going to do you much good.</li><li style="">Personally, I wouldn't worry about Kinect. While the Xbox One version is supposed to be better, it doesn't really get much support anymore. I'm not sure what on the platform is worth getting it for that you couldn't already do on the 360, and it's pretty expensive. That the Kinect version seem to be bundled with Assassin's Creed Unity seems to be one extra reason to stay away.</li></ul><br />
<br />
So, if you do trade in your old console:<br />
<br />
$250 500 Gig bundle + Free game<br />
$300 1TB bundle + Free game<br />
$400 Elite system - Only Gamestop seems to offer a free game with this one. It's very expensive but technically a good value, as the controller retails for $150 or so, and it comes with a hybrid drive.<br />
<br />
And if you don't trade in your old console:<br />
<br />
$300 500 Gig bundle + Free game (though since it's a gift card, you could get multiple cheaper games)<br />
$350 1TB bundle - no free game, though it does include a Tomb Raider bundle as an option<br />
<br />
For those that want to know all their options on the generic $50 off deal, here are all the different games featured in their two million bundles. Tomb Raider and Fallout 4 are standouts, I think. The main drawback to the 500 gig bundle isn't the size of the hard drive as much as the quality of the packaged game, in my opinion.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px"><b>Spoiler</b> for <i>bundled games</i>: <input type="button" value="Show" style="width:45px;font-size:10px;margin:0px;padding:0px;" onClick="if (this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display != 'inline') { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'inline'; this.value = 'Hide'; } else { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'none';  this.value = 'Show'; }">
